On 23 July, Thousands of protesters tried to march to the [[Egyptian Army#Structure|Defense Ministry]] of Egypt in [[Cairo]] when they were attacked by groups of men wielding knives, sticks, , stones and [[Molotov cocktail|molotov cocktails]].<ref name="guardian1">{{cite web|author=Associated Press |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/jul/24/egypt-protest-march-military-council |title=Egyptian protest march descends into violent clashes | World news | guardian.co.uk |publisher=Guardian |date= |accessdate=2011-07-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://af.reuters.com/article/topNews/idAFJOE76N01L20110724?sp=true |title=Scores hurt in clashes, Egypt rulers promise democracy | Top News | Reuters |publisher=Af.reuters.com |date=2009-02-09 |accessdate=2011-07-24}}</ref> It was the second time in two days that crowds had tried to march to the headquarters<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-14265772 |title=BBC News - Clashes at Egypt demonstrations for political change |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2011-03-19 |accessdate=2011-07-24}}</ref> located in [[Heliopolis]]. The march started moving from [[Tahrir Square]] at 4:00 PM, picking up more and more protesters as the march went onto Ramsis and then to the eastern Abbasiya neighbourhood where it was stopped by army barricades.<ref name="guardian1"/> The march was a reaction to the SCAF accused [[6 April Youth Movement]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/~/NewsContent/1/64/17141/Egypt/Politics-/Thousands-start-marching-from-Tahrir-heading-to-mi.aspx |title=Thousands start marching from Egypt's Tahrir heading to military council HQ - Politics - Egypt - Ahram Online |publisher=English.ahram.org.eg |date= |accessdate=2011-07-24}}</ref> and [[Kefaya]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bikyamasr.com/wordpress/?p=37180 |title=Egypt burning: Abbassiya march erupts in violence |publisher=Bikya Masr |date= |accessdate=2011-07-24}}</ref> of treason and that their movements are harming "national interests" a day earlier. The violence broke out following a televised speech commemorating the [[Egyptian Revolution of 1952|1952 coup]] by Field Marshal [[Mohammed Hussein Tantawi]], head of the ruling military council, who attempted to diffuse tensions by praising young people who led the uprising that toppled [[Mubarak]]<ref>http://af.reuters.com/article/topNews/idAFJOE76N01L20110724?sp=true</ref><ref>http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-14265772</ref>. The clashes broke out after civilians threw rocks from rooftops in adjacent buildings. Many in the crowd were thought by protesters to be thugs but some residents of the Abbassiya district were fearful protests in their neighborhood were obstructing business and normalcy. State media said the civilians fighting with the demonstrators were from "people's committees" protecting the neighborhood and the army had maintained all self-restraint, blaming the violence on protesters. Some Abbasiya residents appeared to believe protesters were seeking to create rifts between the army and the people<ref>url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/23/us-egypt-protests-idUSTRE76M1G320110723</ref>. Military police, armed with Tasers and batons, fired in the air to stop the demonstrators from approaching the Defense Ministry. A Reuters witness said tear gas fumes were wafting outside the area as military helicopters circled overhead. The Health Ministry told state television at least 143 people were hurt in the violence<ref>url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/23/us-egypt-protests-idUSTRE76M1G320110723</ref>.

The July 23rd march onto the Ministry of Defense Headquarters started moving from [[Tahrir Square]] at 4:00 PM, picking up more and more protesters as the march went onto Ramsis and then to Abbasiya. The clashes broke out after civilians threw rocks from rooftops in adjacent buildings. Many in the crowd were thought by protesters to be thugs but some residents of the Abbassiya district were fearful protests in their neighborhood were obstructing business and normalcy. State media said the civilians fighting with the demonstrators were from "people's committees" protecting the neighborhood and the army had maintained all self-restraint, blaming the violence on protesters. A Reuters witness said tear gas fumes were wafting outside the area as military helicopters circled overhead. The Health Ministry told state television at least 143 people were hurt in the violence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Scores hurt in clashes, Egypt rulers promise democracy|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/23/us-egypt-protests-idUSTRE76M1G320110723|accessdate=24 July 2011|newspaper=http://www.reuters.com/|date=23 July 2011}}</ref>
